Wolbachia Infection Frequency

The Model

From (Turelli, Katznelson, and Ginsberg 2022), see also (Turelli and Barton 2022).

\[ \begin{align} p_{t+1} &= \frac{p_{t}F(1 - \mu)}{1 + p_{t}(F - 1 - s_{h}) + p_{t}^{2}s_{h}(1 - \mu F)}, \\ q_{ij} &= \left(\begin{array}{c} N \\ j \end{array}\right)(p^{\ast})^{j}(1 - p^{\ast})^{N - j}. \end{align} \]

Implementation

The first equation above is implemented as infection_frequency_step in the script R/infection_frequency.R.

Code 
infection_frequency_step <- function(p_t,F_val,mu_val,sh_val){
  
  num_exp <- p_t*F_val*(1-mu_val)
  den_exp <- 1 + p_t*(F_val - 1 - sh_val) + (p_t^2)*sh_val*(1 - mu_val*F_val)
  
  p_t1 <- num_exp/den_exp
  
  return(max(0.0,min(p_t1,1.0)))
  
}

The function turelli_iteration in the script R/infection_frequency.R implements a time step with both equations above and where \(F\) is a lognormal random variable.

Code 
turelli_iteration <- function(p_val,F_val_m,F_val_CV,
                              sh_val,mu_val,N){
  
  F_val_r <- rnorm(1, mean=log(F_val_m), sd=sqrt(log(F_val_CV^2 + 1))) |>
    exp()
  p_star <- infection_frequency_step(p_val, F_val_r, mu_val, sh_val)
  
  return(rbinom(1, N, p_star) / N )
  
}

The function turelli_simulation in R/infection_frequency.R runs the simulation for a given set of parameters.

Code 
turelli_simulation <- function(p_0,F_val_m,F_val_CV,
                               sh_val,mu_val,N,
                               max_iter=10^10, thresh = 10^(-8)){
  
  gen_i <- 0
  
  while (gen_i < max_iter & p_0 > thresh){
    p_0 <- turelli_iteration(p_0,F_val_m=F_val_m,F_val_CV=F_val_CV,
                             sh_val=sh_val,mu_val=mu_val,N=N)
    gen_i <- gen_i + 1
  }
  
  return(gen_i)
  
}

FigureÂ 1 shows an example simulation based on turelli_simulation. For this simulation, we set \(s_{h} = 0\) and \(\mu = 0.02\). The initial frequency of infection is \(p_{0} = 0.4\). The mean of the lognormal distribution for \(F\) is \(1.021\) and the coefficient of variation is \(0.4\). The effective population size is \(N = 1000\).

Code 
p_0 <- 0.4
F_val_m <- 1.021
F_val_CV <- 0.4

mu_val <- 0.02
sh_val <- 0.0

N <- 1000

p <- turelli_simulation_p(p_0,F_val_m,F_val_CV,
                          sh_val,mu_val,N)

tibble(p=p) |>
  ggplot(aes(x=1:length(p),y=p)) +
  geom_point() +
  ylim(c(0,1)) + 
  labs(x = "Generation", y = "Frequency of infection")

Results

The script turelli_et_al_2022_fig_02.R contains code to reproduce Figure 2 from (Turelli, Katznelson, and Ginsberg 2022). That is, we run multiple simulations (25 per parameter setting) as in turelli_simulation for a range of \(s_{h}\) values and for two choices of the mean of the lognormal distribution, so that \(Median_{F} = 1.021\) and \(Median_{F} = 1.05\). The results are saved in in the data files model_results/fig_02_data_1.csv and model_results/fig_02_data_2.csv.

Code 
# Read in data
df_1 <- read_csv("model_results/fig_02_data_1.csv")
df_2 <- read_csv("model_results/fig_02_data_2.csv")

FigureÂ 2 and FigureÂ 3 show the distribution of persistence times for \(Median_{F} = 1.021\) and \(Median_{F} = 1.05\), respectively.

FigureÂ 4 reproduces Figure 2 from (Turelli, Katznelson, and Ginsberg 2022). The results are similar to those in the paper.

Code 
df_1_s <- df_1 |>
  group_by(sh_val) |>
  summarise(mean = mean(t_f), n = n()) |>
  mutate(F_val = "1.021")

df_2_s <- df_2 |>
  group_by(sh_val) |>
  summarise(mean = mean(t_f), n = n())  |>
  mutate(F_val = "1.05")

df_12 <- rbind(df_1_s,df_2_s)

df_12 %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=sh_val, y = mean,color=F_val)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_y_log10(breaks = trans_breaks("log10", function(x) 10^x),
                labels = trans_format("log10", math_format(10^.x))) + 
  scale_color_colorblind() +
  labs(x = TeX("$s_{h}$"), y = TeX("$\\hat{E}(T_{Loss})$"), color=TeX("$Median_{F}$"))
